Orient Overseas Declines After ‘Disappointing’ Outlook for 2011

-- B y   J a s m i n e   W a n g
-- 
2011-07-20T08:39:51Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-20/orient-overseas-declines-after-disappointing-outlook-for-2011.html
Orient Overseas (International) Ltd.
fell to its lowest level in 18 months in  Hong Kong  trading after
the container-shipping line said outlook for the full year is
“disappointing” because of declining freight rates.  The stock dropped 1.5 percent to HK$45.85 at the 4 p.m.
close in Hong Kong, the lowest level since Jan. 8, 2010. The
benchmark  Hang Seng Index  rose 0.5 percent.  “Freight rates on east-west trades have further
deteriorated over the course of the second quarter, particularly
on the Asia-Europe trades,” Orient Overseas said in a statement
to Hong Kong’s stock exchange today. “The outlook for the full
year is disappointing.”  Load factor, or the percentage of capacity sold, dropped
8.3 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier, the
company said. Sales rose 1.4 percent to $1.4 billion in the
quarter and volume of freight shipped increased by 6.5 percent,
it said.  To contact the reporters on this story:
Jasmine Wang in Hong Kong at 
